article.headline: Indiana 61, Minnesota 46
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jenny DeMuth wasn't ready to let the NCAA's
selection committee determine how her Indiana career would end. So
the fifth-year senior took control Friday night.

DeMuth's hard drives to the basket got Indiana's struggling
offense in sync -- and her teammates responded. Nikki Smith tied a
career-high with 18 points, while DeMuth finished with 14 points
and seven rebounds to lead the sixth-seeded Hoosiers past No. 20
Minnesota 61-46 in the only upset of Friday's Big Ten
quarterfinals.

Afterward, DeMuth walked to center court where her teammates
hugged her before gathering in a huddle -- grins all around.

"I think we were just going in and executing our game plan,
we're going to leave it on the floor," DeMuth said. "I don't
think we went in thinking we needed to win."

But a victory sure helped their resume.

It's the first time Indiana (17-12) has reached the semifinals
since winning the title in 2002. The victory also kept alive the
Hoosiers' hopes of breaking their own tourney record as the
lowest-seeded team to win the championship. Indiana was the fifth
seed in 2002.

Now the Hoosiers must prepare for Sunday's rematch with No. 14
Purdue in the first postseason meeting between the instate rivals
since the 2002 Big Ten semis. The Boilermakers advanced Friday with
a 68-57 victory over Illinois.

For third-seeded Minnesota (19-9), it was another inexplicably
poor performance in Indianapolis. The Golden Gophers lost in the
title game last year -- the only time they've moved beyond the
quarterfinals -- and are now 4-13 all-time in the conference
tournament.

What went wrong? Everything.

The Gophers shot 30.9 percent from the field, committed 20
turnovers, 21 fouls and never got their offense working. Leading
scorer Jamie Broback had eight points and six turnovers, and the
only player to reach double figures was backup Liz Podominick with
11 points.

Minnesota must now await its postseason fate before getting
another shot at a fifth-straight 20-win season.

Even Broback acknowledged the one glaring problem Friday:
Indiana's unnerving mixture of defenses caused havoc.

"This was a very disappointing display of basketball," coach
Pam Borton said. "When you shoot 31 percent and have 20 turnovers,
you're not going to win, especially in March."

At times, the game was as ugly as it was surprising. After
nearly 13 minutes, the teams were mired in a 13-7 slugfest that
included 16 turnovers between the two teams.

But it was just what the hard-charging DeMuth and her teammates
needed to upset a foe that won both games during the regular
season.

"We changed up our defense more, our ball pressure on the
guards was amazing," DeMuth said. "I think all around, we just
got after it."

Indiana wasted no time in making a statement.

The defense opened the game by shutting out Minnesota for nearly
four minutes and yielding only one basket in the first eight
minutes. By that point, the Gophers had already dug themselves into
a 10-2 hole.

They rallied late in the half, getting three 3-pointers from
Shannon Schonrock to close within 23-20 in the last minute. But
Minnesota's 12th turnover led to Cyndi Valentin's breakaway layup
and the Gophers never got closer than three again.

Minnesota struggled in the second half, too. After Broback
opened with a putback to make it 25-22, the Hoosiers pulled away
with an 11-0 run that began with Smith's 3 and ended with DeMuth's
10-foot runner.

A late 8-0 run gave Indiana a 50-33 lead, and Minnesota never
challenged again.

Freshman Whitney Thomas had 10 points and nine rebounds, but it
was DeMuth who provided the spark -- and possibly a victory that
could catapult Indiana into the NCAA tournament, regardless of what
happens during rest of the Big Ten tourney.

"This is a huge win for our players and our program," Hoosiers
coach Sharon Versyp said. "We really executed our game plan to the
tee. We hit every goal that we set."
